data.enText: to say words for sb else to write down
He dictated a letter to his secretary.

data.chText: （尤指以令人不快的方式）指使，强行规定
data.enText: to tell sb what to do, especially in an annoying way

data.chText: 他们没有资格发号施令。
data.enText: They are in no position to dictate terms (= tell other people what to do) .

data.chText: 他们有什么权利强行规定我们该怎样生活？
data.enText: What right do they have to dictate how we live our lives?
to control or influence how sth happens

data.chText: 我们什么时候休假在很大程度上取决于格雷格的工作计划。
data.enText: When we take our vacations is very much dictated by Greg's work schedule.

data.chText: 一般说来，你住在什么地方是由你的工作决定的。
data.enText: It's generally your job that dictates where you live now.

data.chText: 任意指使某人；向某人发号施令
data.enText: to give orders to sb, often in a rude or aggressive way
She refused to be dictated to by anyone.
an order or a rule that you must obey
to follow the dictates of fashion

simple_means.memory_skill: dict 说；断言 + ate 表动词 → 说话 → 口授

means: (尤指以令人不快的方式)指使，强行规定

data.chText: 任意指使某人；向某人发号施令
data.enText: to give orders to sb, often in a rude or aggressive way
She refused to be dictated to by anyone.

tr: say out loud for the purpose of recording
example: He dictated a report to his secretary

value.boxr_value: The verb is pronounced /dɪk'teɪt, am  'dɪkteɪt/. The noun is pronounced /'dɪkteɪt/. 动词读作/dɪk'teɪt, 美 'dɪkteɪt/。名词读作/'dɪkteɪt/。

value.def: If you dictate something, you say or read it aloud for someone else to write down.

example.ex: Sheldon writes every day of the week, dictating his novels in the morning...
example.tran: 谢尔登一周 7 天都要写作，每天早上口述小说让别人记录。

example.ex: Everything he dictated was signed and sent out the same day.
example.tran: 他口授的所有内容都签上名并在同一天寄出了。

value.def: If someone dictates to someone else, they tell them what they should do or can do.

example.ex: He had warned the West against trying to dictate to the Soviet Union...
example.tran: 他警告西方国家不要试图对苏联发号施令。

example.ex: What right has one country to dictate the environmental standards of another?...
example.tran: 一个国家有什么权力强行给另一个国家制定环境标准？

example.ex: He cannot be allowed to dictate what can and cannot be inspected...
example.tran: 什么能检查什么不能检查不能由他说了算。

example.ex: What gives them the right to dictate to us what we should eat?...
example.tran: 他们有什么权利来规定我们应该吃什么？

example.ex: The officers were more or less able to dictate terms to successive governments...
example.tran: 这些军官多多少少都能和继任的各届政府谈些条件。

example.ex: The rules of court dictate that a defendant is entitled to all evidence which may help his case.
example.tran: 法庭规定被告可以出示任何对其辩护有帮助的证据。

value.tran: 命令;发号施令;强行规定

value.def: If one thing dictates another, the first thing causes or influences the second thing.

example.ex: The film's  budget dictated a tough schedule...
example.tran: 影片的预算决定了拍摄进度会很紧张。

example.ex: The way in which they dress is dictated by very rigid fashion rules...
example.tran: 他们的着装受到时尚规则的严格限制。

example.ex: Of course, a number of factors will dictate how long an apple tree can survive...
example.tran: 当然，影响一棵苹果树寿命的因素有很多。

example.ex: Circumstances dictated that they played a defensive rather than attacking game.
example.tran: 比赛形势决定了他们要打防守战而不是进攻战。

value.def: You say that reason or common sense dictates that a particular thing is the case when you believe strongly that it is the case and that reason or common sense will cause other people to agree.

example.ex: Commonsense now dictates that it would be wise to sell a few shares.
example.tran: 现在，常识告诉我们卖掉一些股票是明智的。

value.def: A dictate is an order which you have to obey.

example.ex: Their job is to ensure that the dictates of the Party are followed.
example.tran: 他们的工作就是确保党的指示得到执行。

gramarinfo.label: usu with supp, oft N <l>of</l> n

value.def: Dictates are principles or rules which you consider to be extremely important.

example.ex: We have followed the dictates of our consciences and have done our duty.
example.tran: 我们遵从了自己的良知，尽到了自己的义务。

gramarinfo.label: usu pl, with supp, usu N <l>of</l> n
